Please follow the easiest method to correct the boot menu using the Boot-Repair method for Ubuntu 
- - [ 100% working for all types of BIOS. ] - - -

Check bios on your system (LINUX)
sudo apt install efibootmgr
sudo efibootmgr

Check bios type on your system (Windows 10)
search for 
System Information
Step 0 Follow the installation process-

Part-1 For legacy BIOS
Part-2 For UEFI

******************************************************
------------------------------------------------------
No EFI System Partition was found Ubuntu Error Solved
------------------------------------------------------
******************************************************

Follow the easy steps written below:
Step 1- Power off your Linux desktop or restart it once.

Step 2- Press the keys to load the boot menu. For example F7 or ESC 

Step 3- Select the Disk UEFI (to boot with) and hit enter.

Step 4- Select *Ubuntu and hit enter. Wait until disk check gets completed.

Step 5- Click on Try Ubuntu

Step 6- Open the terminal or press ctrl+t.

Step 7- Note: Everything we are going to do will be temporary to fix the boot loader issue. Once you disconnect the USB stick everything will be wiped from the test os.

Now we will run some commands to fix things:
#- - - Add a repository to install boot-repair:
sudo add-apt-repository ppa:yannubuntu/boot-repair

#- - - Update:
sudo apt-get update

#- - - Install boot-repair:
sudo apt-get install boot-repair

Step 8- Close the terminal and open Boot Repair from Ubuntu Menu.

Step 9- Wait for some time. Click on the Recommended repair (first option). It will identify your system type and try to fix everything.

Step 10- Press y to upload the report. It will create all the boot information inside the EFI boot loader.

Press 11- you will see an error in front of you. Ignore that and Turn off the system.

Step 12- Remove the disk and hit enter.

